The house in bones fascinates even after 100 years. Take a look inside Gaudi.
The toy looks like the back of a prehistoric saurian, the staircase to a dinosaur spine, and the balconies to open fish bowls.
This is the Casa Battlo house in Barcelona by the architect Antoni Gaudi.
Due to its organic forms, the house received from the locals the nickname "House in Bone".
Organic forms, wild colors, unusual use of stones, fragments of tiles and mosaic, facade reminiscent of scales and everywhere present curves, this is all that is typical of Antoni Gaudi’s New Art.
The front fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade of the house unfolds its dream lines, its pleasant colors and textures that remind nature and animals.
In the course of a more detailed observation we see the geometry, the rhythm and the order thought with precision.
At night the facade of the house becomes even more dramatic and is lit in such a way that the impression of brightness of the colors is reinforced by it.
The winding and twisting of the shapes also appears in the interiors with the same measure.
The wood in waves copies the window frames, balustrades, decorative elements of the doors, the eyelash and the lamellas.
The Battlo house that stands in the Eixample district in the shopping street Passeig de Gracia at number 43, was born from the construction of an 1877 house by the architect Emilio Sala Cortes.
The reconstruction took place for two years and the house was completed in 1906.
The investor, Joseph Battlo, a wealthy entrepreneur, first insisted on demolishing the old building and building another brand new one but quickly accepted Gaudi's idea of an unusual and cheaper reconstruction.
But the idea of Casa Battlo as a multi-dwelling house was not thought by Gaudi alone.
The architect Josep Maria Jujol worked with him.
It is precisely on his project that the decorations for an apartment representing the owner of the building and the use of the mosaic for the facade were born.
Other artists and creators have also worked for the facade.
The joint work for the plans of the Casa Battlo house began with a successful cooperation between Jujol and Gaudi.
Jujol participated in the construction of the house of Gaudi Casa Mila and Guell Park in which there are other works of Gaudi.
The locals nicknamed the warm house just after it was finished because of its organic forms "the House in Bone".
Others, given the specific mechanism of opening the windows, called it "the house that dances".
It is said that at the top of the building there is a sword similar to that of Saint George, the patron saint of Catalonia.
Other elements of sculpture of the construction contain hidden religious motifs.
Gaudi thought for the house a unique system in its central heating time, with ventilation vents and typical fireplaces.
Their inclination of 45 degrees seems strange.
During the creation of Gaudi absolutely did not comply with the construction guidelines of the time and did not let themselves be hindered by them.
At the beginning of construction he obtained permission from the city to build, knowing, of course, that the data carried on the reconstruction plans were so vague that two years later during the completion the municipal council was horrified and requested modifications.
He did not like, for example, the members of the municipal council that the pillars of construction are plying on the public sidewalk.
There was never a change, but, on the contrary, only 15 days after the city's appeal Josep Battlo requested (and obtained satisfaction) permission to rent the two highest floors.
The owner moved to the lower floors.
In the gallery on the second floor there was a common living room and on the third a bedroom and a private part of the apartment.
The ground floor was rented to a jewelry store.
The entire six-storey house is shared by a staircase through which one can access up to an independent roof terrace.
All right angles and straight lines were cancelled by the basic elements of the reconstruction and replaced by curved walls.
Gaudi also worked on the modern concept of linking spaces.
The common part can be fully connected by opening the doors of the salons and the high society can communicate comfortably or limit private space for more intimate interviews.
The house with the reconstruction of Gaudi received in addition new facades a non-traditional roof and two additional floors.
Gaudi’s play with light is also impressive, with blue and white glass tiles with which the inner courtyard is decorated and with light wells.
The two-color game gives a maximum of light in all floors of the house.
It was simply enough to bet on the principle that white reflects more than dark, which on the contrary absorbs the sun’s rays.
The Casa Battlo house that was registered in 2005 in the UNESCO World Heritage Fund may be visited by everyone.
On the first floor of the house is the most spacious and the most beautiful apartment accessible to the public.
The owners decided to pass this step in 2002 on the occasion of the 150th anniversary of the birth of the famous creator.
They continued the visits because they found it to be a lucrative business and they expanded the field of visits to the common spaces and the barn including the toy terraces.
The entrance ticket to the monument is not really expensive and costs 16.50 euros; students, retirees, groups and tourist card holders have 20 percent discount.
The sum is still above the entry price into the other Gaudi buildings in the city.
If you want to feel the real atmosphere of the house with its fantastic towers, you must quickly find a comrade among the inhabitants of the building and visit the house completely.
