Devices to track people are increasingly being asked by parents who want to monitor their children.
The fear of their child leads more and more people to think about watching them through a GPS.
The system, set up at the beginning to search for cars can just as well be used to track the movement of people and help in some cases as for example that of little Anicka Janatkova.
The instrument is currently as big as a box of lighters but will soon be the size of a watch.
The case of little Anicka has moved a large number of people and they have begun to look for ways to better protect their children.
Even if the price is to disturb their privacy.
“We’re trying to tell everyone that this is not espionage but just another way to lessen the likelihood of another tragedy,” said Petr Pilin of MACRO Weil, one of the Czech market’s leading providers of tracking devices.
"I admit that there may be cases of misuse of such devices, such as putting it in the bag of someone who is not aware, but I have not yet encountered such cases."
“Most people are customers who actually buy the product for safety reasons,” Pilin added.
According to him, children should always know what purpose is used "the box" and how to use it in an emergency.
The child psychologist, Dana Bockova, draws attention that if the child does not want to wear such a thing on him, he will get rid of it.
“Even the youngest can show great creativity when it comes to getting rid of something explicitly when they don’t want to be under control.”
“Mobile phones, which can be cut off like these tracking devices, have already led parents to long-awaited,” Bockova says.
According to her, the fact that this type of device can help in case of aggression is highly questionable.
"If this is a ready-made robbery, the author will do everything to ensure that the child does not have an electronic device that can locate it."
“At the moment, it’s the phone.”
"As soon as the tracking devices are developed, they (the criminals) will look for them as well because the sale will be supported by an advertising campaign."
“In such cases, the criminals will always be in advance on the police,” says the psychologist.
It also admits that such devices can help in an attack not prepared by a pedophile.
According to Robert Cech of RC Monitoring, which offers tracking services for both cars and people, he claims that having this type of device can help, even if it is destroyed in the event of an attack.
"The device may be set in such a way that it is regularly broadcast after a specified period."
"In the event that the device is destroyed, it still remains the last position of the person concerned."
“The more expensive devices also have an inclinometer that immediately signals the position of the person who slipped and is in an elongated position without moving,” says Cech.
According to him, so-called smartphones that are equipped with a navigation system, can offer a comparable service after having formatted it with a special software.
The problem with the current tracking systems is that it is either a device similar to those worn in a pendant the size of a box of lighters or the smallest telephone devices.
We can always lose them.
According to Pilina of Macro Weil, this is why tests are currently being carried out to make devices that look like common digital watches.
"This will have the advantage that the potential attacker will not be able to recognize the tracking device."
“Or he will realize it after a while, which will have given the police a little more time,” he added.
Whether the tracking device is developed in the form of a bracelet or pendant, it will always use the same technology as to track cars.
