Prosecutors will not blame Senator Ensign
Attorneys at the Department of Justice have raised criminal charges against Senator John Ensign, stemming from a case involving a former campaign assistant and his efforts to obtain lobbying work for the woman's husband, the senator's lawyers announced on Wednesday.
The decision ends the most serious legal threat faced by Mr. Ensign, the Republican from Nevada who was considered a possible Republican candidate for the 2012 presidential election until the scandal surrounding his case made the major national headlines last year and damaged his career.
Mr. Ensign's office said he was "very happy" with the decision, the result of a one-year investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary measures taken by the Senate Ethics Committee.
Mr. Ensign's lawyers stated that the Justice Department had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer the subject of the investigation and that he had no intention of holding any charge against him in this case."
The Ministry of Justice has refrained from commenting on the matter.
The announcement came as a sort of surprise for many ethics lawyers outside the Justice Department, according to which there is significant evidence that Mr. Ensign had conspired to violate a federal lobbying ban.
Interviews, emails and other documents, first released in October 2009 in the New York Times, indicated that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, get a lucrative lobbying job to gain the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife about it.
Mrs. Hampton once served as a cashier during an Ensign campaign.
Mr. Ensign contacted a number of political funders to find work for Mr. Hampton and then defended their rights after they hired Mr. Hampton to lobby for them; in accordance with the documents and interviews.
Given that Mr. Hampton had recently been an employee of Mr. Ensign, he was prohibited for one year by law from lobbying with his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr. Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the case, appears to be in contradiction with the so-called ban on the revolving door of lobbying.
According to the evidence that has been made public, "there seems to be prima facie evidence of a plot to violate and substantially violate the law of the revolving door," said Stanley Brand, a Washington lawyer who specializes in defending clients of a government investigation.
Although the department judge declined to explain the reasoning that led to the decision in the Ensign case, Mr. Brand and other ethics lawyers said that the department seemed to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of high-level setbacks for his last year's arrest, including those who had been convicted of the crime.
Federal prosecutors are clearly afraid to take up arms, said Melanie Sloan, the Citizens’ Director General for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a defense group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"This basically says high-ranking government officials can now assume the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins, Ensign’s chief attorney, said in an interview Monday that he had received a phone call from a prosecutor from the Department of Justice and a follow-up the next day, telling him that the department was not seeking charges against his client.
Mr. Ensign's team of lawyers had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office reaffirmed on Wednesday in a statement, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr. Coggins declined to clarify the legal arguments he had made at the prosecutor's office.
“I’m not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Justice Department, except to say that we think they made the right decision,” he said.
Last month, the Federal Election Commission decided to drop an investigation following an independent complaint by the ethics group, arguing that Mr. Ensign's parents' $96,000 payment was in violation of federal election law.
The Electoral Commission said it did not have enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada company that has long supported the senator, is a company for which Mr. Ensign helped Mr. Hampton find lobbying work.
An email sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company welcomed Mr. Hampton as a lobbyist, Ensign's chief of staff, John Lopez, contacted Mr. Hampton and told him he was "marting" the Interior Ministry on a matter in dispute.
Mr. Ensign also attended a luncheon with Mr. Hampton and another Nevada customer, Allegiant Air, and he asked the Secretary of Transportation to set up a meeting on behalf of the airline after engaging Mr. Hampton in lobbying.
When the news of the case surfaced last year, Mr. Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as the fourth Republican in the Senate.
After maintaining a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intended to run for a third term in the Senate.
Announcing that Mr. Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said the senator hoped that the ethics committee would quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and put an end to his investigation.
Senator Ensign is pleased to continue his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, she said.
