Can civilization bring the splits closer together?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility broke out in Washington this week.
Is it a sign of genuine bipartisan cooperation forward or an illusory moment before the quick return to partisan struggle in the capital?
Tuesday’s meeting between President Obama and the leaders of Congress did not produce any breakthroughs on the major issues that need to be addressed during the “boxy duck” session.
But obviously, there has been at least one polished discussion about the differences between the two parties as well as the recognition of their shared responsibilities to govern, rather than another episode where each camp wanted to score points.
The committee’s public meeting on the president’s deficit was equally civilised, despite the political differences that remain between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months created a mutual respect transcending the ideological divide; but which, however, still divides the members.
It is hardly enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two sides are now in a trial and trial period with a view to obtaining signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a renewed partisan war.
That’s why Tuesday’s meeting and subsequent comments from participants revealed a minimum of requirements or charges.
The philosophical differences between Obama and Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid change in the climate that has existed over the past two years.
Whether it’s taxation, spending, health care or rights, both parties remain miles away.
However, the November election had moderated Washington, at least in the short term.
“There’s no doubt that things have changed on the pitch,” said Pete Wehner, a Bush administration official, now alongside the Center for Ethical and Public Policy.
“It’s inevitable after the election.
The elections generate partisan passions, and then they cease to exist.
That's good."
On some issues, including those on the agenda for the "boxy duck" session, Republicans and Democrats have no choice but to find a solution.
Bush’s tax cuts will expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favor of that.
Both parties want to find a way to preserve some or all of it, permanently or temporarily.
Similarly, a compromise is conceivable on the extension of unemployment benefits, only because Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favor of tax cuts for the rich, while denying unemployment benefits to the unemployed.
After Tuesday's meeting at the White House, more optimism is on a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on the "boxy duck", with the ratification of the "New START" pact.
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution warns that a fruitful cooperation on the most pressing issues of the "lame duck" session will not necessarily lead to a better agreement between the two parties when the 112th Congress meets in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, or even inevitable.
“Once the things that need to be done are done, psychology in the short term will return to one of the confrontations,” he said.
Wehner also expressed his widely shared skepticism that civilization would lead to true cooperation.
"I consider most of what is happening between today and 2012 as a pre-show or shadow boxing compared to the 2012 main event," he said.
The reasons for this are closely related to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters present in the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know that they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and repeal the new Health Care Act.
These partisan positions are already clear in the early reactions to the recommendations of the deficit committee, which include reforming the tax code and increasing certain taxes, delaying the retirement age and reducing spending.
Co-chairs Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles have chosen one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, according to themselves, imposed the question of the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they needed 14 votes in the committee, made up of 18 members, to issue their plan as an official recommendation, and they had trouble reaching that number.
The greatest resistance persists among the group's elected representatives, suggesting that there are, at least today, few grounds or will to compromise on tax matters.
Galston plans two phases in the fighting between the White House and the Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan clashes, as Republicans challenge Obama in terms of budget, taxes and health care, followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What would be the cause of the change?
The public opinion.
It is widely proven that, despite the partisan spirit of the recent election, a majority of Americans still want to see the two parties work together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as in 1995, then the two parties will carefully observe the reaction of the public.
Those who will be judged in loss will have to change their minds and find compromises.
But that would still be an optimistic point of view.
The partisan spirit and polarization are greater today than they were in the mid-1990s and there seems to be a greater ideological gap between Obama and the Republicans in Congress than there was then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, activists from both parties see 2010 as a simple prelude to a more consistent election in 2012.
Given this reality, the civilization exhibited this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on both sides to find a consensus on the issues that still divide them.
