The European Union changes the rules for obtaining a visa
Individuals must go to Visa Applicants Service Centers prior to their interview in the Consular Section; the cost of waiting time will be lower.
As of January 10, 2011, the visa processing procedure at the U.S. Embassy and Consulates will change.
With the new procedure, the majority of applicants will have to appear at Visa Applicants Service Centers (ASC) prior to their interview in the Consular Section.
CSA staff will take the applicant's biometric information, which will be reviewed by the Consular Section prior to the interview.
The new procedure will have some benefits for applicants, including the following:
The total cost to process the visa will be lower, it will no longer be necessary to make a payment to obtain an appointment, another payment for the processing of the visa and another for the mail service to deliver the document.
The aspirant will make a single payment that will cover all three services.
The current rate will remain the same: the equivalent of $140 for a tourist visa, $150 for visas with application (including visas for temporary workers) and $390 for visas for traders and investors.
Those who wish to renew their visa will not be required to attend an interview with the Consular Representative, they will only be present at the nearest ASC where they will present the documents and their fingerprints will be taken.
Due to the fact that biometric information will be included in the CSA, applicants who wish to have a second appointment to be interviewed in the Consular Section will have less time than before.
Similarly, visa applicants to the Consulates of Ciudad Ju<0xC3><0xA1>rez, Monterrey and Nuevo Laredo will no longer pay the additional $26 service fee.
For more information on the new visa application procedure, visit the following page http://mexico.usembassy.gov/newspapers/sp101201_Visas-FAQs.html
