A Global Plan to Renovate Lighting
The United Nations has proposed a plan to renovate domestic, commercial and industrial lighting in 100 countries to achieve a greenhouse gas (GHG) reduction that corresponds to almost a third of the additional reduction needed to stabilize the global climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan is in the wake of the major concrete projects that the UN hopes will be adopted in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding reduction commitments by industrialized countries.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent bulbs that monopolize still 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by fluocompact bulbs or, better, by electroluminescent diode bulbs (DEL or "LED" in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion Euclidean tons (Gt) would be replaced.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is the equivalent of 70% of the emissions from the global automotive park.
In Copenhagen last year, major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, committed to voluntary reduction plans that are expected to drive global GHG emissions from 53 Gt to 49 Gt.
But it will be necessary to remove another 5 Gt from this balance sheet in order to stabilize the rise of the climate to 2 degrees centigrade by 2020 in order to avoid it becoming out of control.
In the incandescent bulbs, 95% of the energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the rest, or 5%, is produced by light.
With fluocompact bulbs, the energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new LED bulbs, this need for energy is reduced twice more.
Fluocompact bulbs last on average from 6000 to 10,000 hours.
The new LED bulbs, such as those launched by manufacturer Philips this week - this company has also participated in the UN study - have a lifespan of 25,000 hours and consume 80% less energy than an incandescent bulb, which gives a possible idea of the economy with a replacement plan.
These all-new bulbs can also work with rheostats in addition to emit very little heat.
They do not contain any mercury.
Several specialists have posted reservations at the site of fluocompact bulbs since they contain mercury and need to be disposed of as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless manufacturers put in place instructions.
But, according to the report, the main source of mercury emission on the planet is not the fluocompact bulb, but rather the coal-fired thermal power plants, which emit a lot of mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent bulbs.
In the United States alone, these plants emit 25,000 tons of mercury per year.
The report details the gains each country would make through this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save $1 billion a year in electricity purchases and eight million tons of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 thermal power plants, whose construction would cost it $2.5 billion.
