This is the mechanism of Dan Brown’s success.
I'm going for the secret files.
The informant is lazy, and lazy (or with a limited mind) the head of the secret services (otherwise it could be, as far as I know, editor at Liberation), who retains as true only what he recognizes.
Top secret information about Berlusconi that the U.S. Embassy in Rome sent to the State Department was the same as that Newsweek published the week before.
So why did the revelations on these files make so much noise?
On the one hand, they say what every cultivated person already knows, namely that embassies, at least since the end of World War II, and since heads of state can call or take a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic function and, with the exception of a few small exercises in the center of the country, they have lost their diplomatic function.
Any investigative film viewer knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that one pretends to ignore it.
However, the fact of repeating it publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to place American diplomacy in a bad light.
Secondly, the idea that any hacker can capture the world’s most powerful country’s most secretive secrets carries a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
Also, the scandal does not put the victims as much into crisis as the “burreaux”.
But let’s get to the deep nature of what happened.
Once upon a time, in Orwell’s time, one could conceive of any power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The Orwellian prophecy had been fully proven since, being able to control every movement through the telephone, every transaction made, the hotel visited, the highway borrowed and so on, the citizen became the total victim of the eye of power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it is now, that even the crypts of the secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the control relationship ceases to be one-way and becomes circular.
Power controls every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as the citizen's revenger - can know all the secrets of power.
How can a power that no longer has the ability to keep its own secrets hold?
It is true, Georg Simmel already said, that a true secret is an empty secret (and an empty secret can never be revealed); it is also true that knowing everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is indeed an empty secret, because it belongs to the public domain; but revealing, as WikiLeaks has done to him, all the secrets of Cly de Hill are hidden.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or Merkel, but it has done too much to Clinton and Obama.
What will be the consequences of this injury inflicted on a very powerful power?
It is obvious that in the future, states will no longer be able to put any reserved information online - this would be to publish it on a poster glued to the corner of the street.
But it’s just as obvious as with current technologies, it’s vain to hope to be able to maintain confidential phone reports.
Nothing is easier than finding out if and when a head of state moved on a plane and contacted one of his colleagues.
How will private and reserved relations be maintained in the future?
I know that, for the time being, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government agents who move discreetly in diligence on uncontrollable routes, being only bearers of messages learned from the heart or, at the very least, in information.
The information will be kept in a single copy in key-closed drawers: in the end, the attempt to spy on Watergate was less successful than WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that the technology is now advancing in crabs, that is to say, backwards.
