Climate: how France contributes to its funding pledges
One year after the Copenhagen Agreement, it is time to review the compliance with the promises of rapidly-unlocked funding (so-called fast start or early funding) made by developed countries.
And the big French boxing is revealed.
In the Copenhagen Agreement, developed countries committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has promised <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion over three years and France <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1.26 billion (i.e. 420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU released the big game to persuade its partners of the reality of its commitment to fast-start finance: report detailing the action of its member states, press conference, big side event, distribution of brochures...
Transparency is valued and valued at its fair value: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU announced that it had released <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion in 2010, putting it on track to meet its <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>7.2 billion commitment in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen Agreement, "new and additional", in order to ensure that an additional effort is made without being at the expense of public development aid.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what "new and additional" means.
While the European Commission had proposed harmonisation, some Member States of which France blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that suits them best.
For example, the European Commission considered 2009 as a reference year: international funding is maintained, and it adds 150 million over three years to fast start funding.
Other countries have chosen similar references in terms of year or in terms of level of public development assistance.
On the contrary, France believes that the funding for "all new projects" in 2010 is "new and additional".
In other words, there is no reference to the expenditures of previous years or the overall level of public development assistance.
In concrete terms, France’s total support to developing countries can remain stable (or even decrease), it claims to respect its commitment to “new and additional” funding...
Another crucial element is the distribution between donations and loans.
There again, there is no rule and everyone chooses his or her method of calculation.
Some, like France, consider that <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 loaned is equivalent to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 given.
Of course, this is difficult to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments that are profitable (often projects related to the mitigation of emissions that are based on more efficient technologies), it is necessary to present a euro that is to be recovered as a euro equivalent to a euro that is being given interest).... At the very least, the country should not be obliged to pay the amount of the loan.
But France only has to make such a reasoning: it “respects” its commitment of 420 million euros by making 91.5% loans (389.8 million euros) and 8.5% donations (36.1 million euros) – see the EU document to check for yourself.
It is the only EU country to use the loan so massively.
Germany requires 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands or Slovakia (among others) fulfill their commitments with 100% donations.
In other words, when the very large majority of the European Union puts <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>1 to meet its commitment, France puts only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Nice pass-by tour!
In short, in its fast-start financing, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of action over time and on the other on the reality of financial effort.
By spending only <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>36.1 million, she succeeds in believing that she spends 420 million "new and additional" in line with her promises.
The manipulation of the Ministry of Finance (because it seems that Bercy has carried out the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why would the other Member States continue to give if it is enough to lend?) and in the negotiations since the developing countries are not complete.
The early funding chapter is just a small, relatively short-term issue compared to the whole of climate discussions.
But it could be one more grain of sand in the immense machine that is UNFCCC.
Let's hope that's not the case.
In any case, it is essential to learn the lessons of this first year of early funding.
First of all, France could announce a change in its accounting system for 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect for its commitments and fairness with other European Union countries.
But above all, France could advance discussions on the issues of long-term financing (another crucial chapter currently discussed): one will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of accounting for loans.
France could change its position to become as progressive on these issues as it is on others.
The hope is therefore based on the new Minister of the Environment, Ms. Kosciusko-Morizet, who will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement about France’s fast start and its vision of “additionality” and the use of loans would naturally increase the level of international confidence needed to advance in the discussions.
Warning to pesticides ingested by children
A 10-year-old child ingests 81 different chemicals in a day, according to a study published Wednesday by the Association Generations Futures (ex-Movement for Rights and Respect for Future Generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no significant statistical value in view of the low number of samples analyzed, but are illustrative of the problem dealt with", bought between July and September the foods usually consumed in four meals and a snack in one day in Paris by a child's supermarket.
These typical meals, including the official recommendations - five fresh fruits and vegetables, three dairy products and 1.5 liters of water per day - as well as snacks, were examined by laboratories looking for chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance of the plate is overwhelming: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as possible or probable carcinogens, and five are classified as certain carcinogens, as well as 37 substances likely to act as endocrine disruptors, according to studies from several institutions such as the International Cancer Research Centre.
"Even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each individual chemical taken are not exceeded, we can see in our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to potentially carcinogenic and/or PE contaminants is worrying," the association notes.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea alone contain more than a dozen possible carcinogen residues and three proven as certain carcinogens as well as nearly twenty residues that may disrupt the hormonal system.
The apple, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack by the study, has traces of six chemicals, one of which is still banned in France.
The same is true for Kenya’s green beans, including lunch, where the study detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
In addition, the roasted steak, the tuna in the box, and even the bread baguette and chewing gum were truffled with pesticides and other chemicals.
In tap water, the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the salmon steak was the most "rich" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the plastic plate examination used to heat the microwave meal was not exempt.
The final risk for the consumer of this "contaminant cocktails" "is probably underestimated," according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecology-Les Verts (EE-LV), for its part, proposed "face to the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to stop "increased civilizational diseases".
In July, a study by the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) reported the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruits and vegetables consumed in Europe, including 76 in cereals.
